VARIOUS SPECIES or THE CARAQUATA.

Many species of this plant are commonly to be met with in Paraguay. Ι will briefly men- tion those with which I am best acquainted. The caraquata guazii, or the great caraquata, is supported by a short thick root. It consists of about twenty very thick leaves, dentated on both sideS, remarkably sharp, and about two feet in length, in the midst of which rises a stalk, like a trunk‚ five, and often more feet high. The top of it is crowned with yellow flowers. The Indian women spin threads of the fibres of the leaves, as others do of flax, or hemp, and weave them into cords, cloths, and nets.
